## **Wiring Table**

| Arduino Pin | Component       | Pin Role  | Description                    |
|-------------|-----------------|-----------|--------------------------------|
| **D2**      | 7-Segment Disp. | Segment A | Via 220Ω resistor              |
| **D3**      | 7-Segment Disp. | Segment B | Via 220Ω resistor              |
| **D4**      | 7-Segment Disp. | Segment C | Via 220Ω resistor              |
| **D5**      | 7-Segment Disp. | Segment D | Via 220Ω resistor              |
| **D6**      | 7-Segment Disp. | Segment E | Via 220Ω resistor              |
| **D7**      | 7-Segment Disp. | Segment F | Via 220Ω resistor              |
| **D8**      | 7-Segment Disp. | Segment G | Via 220Ω resistor              |
| **D12**     | Button          | Signal    | Pulled HIGH internally         |
| **GND**     | 7-Segment GND   | —         | Common cathode return          |
| **GND**     | Button GND      | —         | Button return to ground        |

---

## **How It Works**

1. **Button Press Detection**: When you press the button (D12 goes LOW), debouncing logic waits 50ms to ignore bounces.
2. **Counter Increment**: Counter increases by 1 on button release.
3. **Wraparound**: After reaching 9, the counter resets to 0.
4. **Display Update**: The `displayDigit()` function sets the 7 segments to show digits 0–9 using if/else logic.
5. **Segment Mapping**: Each segment pin (D2–D8) drives its segment through a 220Ω current-limiting resistor.

---

## **Power Budget**

| Item | Current |
|------|---------|
| **Per Segment** (7×220Ω @ 5V) | ~20mA each @ max brightness |
| **Max active segments per digit** | 7 segments (digit 8) |
| **Display + Resistors** | ~140mA (peak, all 7 segments lit) |
| **Button circuit** | <1mA (internal pullup) |
| **Arduino D2–D8 pins** | ~20mA each (safe within spec) |
| **Total Board Draw** | ~141mA (well within Arduino Uno 500mA limit) |

**✓ Safe**: All pins individually ≤20mA, total draw comfortably under board limits.

---

